Please enclose this in a try/catch block since it's a generic API. This way, any DBus exceptions can be caught and handled, allowing the operation to continue and return control to the caller. The PEL operation should proceed even if an error occurs, as it operates on a "best effort" basis.


For example,

```
std::optional<DBusPathList> DataInterface::getAssociatedPaths(const std::string& associatedPath, const DBusInterfaceList& interfaces)
{
  try
  {
    ...
  }
  catch (const std::exception& e)
  {
    //add trace
    return std::nullopt;
  } 
}
```

The `GetAssociatedSubTreePaths` method is intended for handling single associations, so we need to use `GetAssociatedSubTreePathsById`. You can refer to [GetAssociatedSubTreePathsById](https://github.com/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/blob/master/yaml/xyz/openbmc_project/ObjectMapper.interface.yaml#L203) for more details. Also, there's a [backend implementation (under review)](https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-objmgr/+/70699), but it's not functioning as expected for our needs. I have [proposed some changes](https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-objmgr/+/70699/8/src/handler.cpp#369) in the backend, which resolve the issue, and it now works as expected.

For example:

```
busctl call -j xyz.openbmc_project.ObjectMapper /xyz/openbmc_project/object_mapper xyz.openbmc_project.ObjectMapper GetAssociatedSubTreePathsById ssassas entry /xyz/openbmc_project 1 xyz.openbmc_project.HardwareIsolation.Entry isolated_hw_errorlog 2 xyz.openbmc_project.Logging.Entry org.open_power.Logging.PEL.Entry
{
	"type" : "as",
	"data" : [
		[
			"/xyz/openbmc_project/logging/entry/599",
			"/xyz/openbmc_project/logging/entry/600"
		]
	]
}
```

We can define a new callback `ProhibitedErrorLogsToDelete`, which will call the above DBus method to return a list of error log IDs. These IDs can then be used in [this location](https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-logging/+/73730/1/log_manager.hpp#129) to avoid the erase call. For non-guard-associated error logs, the `GetAssociatedSubTreePaths` method will not be invoked as the Guard flag will remain false.

@Matt Any thoughts?
